caption: Pantry 279 workers sort through bags of doanted food Nov. 27, 2022, in their space at Trinity Lutheran Church in Elletsville, Indiana. The food pantry, which ran out of food and had to temporarily close in March, is sturggling to meet the holiday demand.

Dawn, a volunteer at the pantry, grabs frozen meals out of one of the coolers the pantry has set up outside Nov. 29, 2022. Because of the COVID-19 pandemic, the pantry operates a drive-through system to make sure it can feed everyone that needs assistance while staying safe.

Stacks of frozen meals in hand, Sandy helps to replinish the supply of food in the outside coolers Nov. 27, 2022. The pantry opened in 2015 after local girl scout troop 69-279 devoted their Silver Award Project to helping their community.

In order to protect the pantry's food from mice, Sandy moves boxes into a meat freezer in the garage of the church Nov. 29, 2022. The volunteers stay bundled up so they can work outside in the harsh winter temperatures.

While the volunteers run the day-to-day operations across town, Pantry 279 director Cindy Chavez gets to work on one of the pantry's additional programs, ELF Dispatch, Dec. 4, 2022, in a donated retail space in a strip mall in Elletsville. The program pairs families in need with communities members who buy items from the children's Christmas lists. Chavez matches each child to their "Santa" by hand.

All of the donated toys sit on shelves in ELF HQ, Chavez's nickname for the space donated by the strip mall's property mangement company each holiday season, on Dec. 4, 2022. While there are still several weeks before donations need to be in, Chavez says she still does not have enough Santas for the nearly 1,600 kids in need of gifts this year.

Chavez talks on the phone while continuing to work through the pile of unmatched children Dec. 4, 2022. Chavez says she works on the ELF Dispatch program every chance she has, working through the day at ELF HQ with the help of an occasional volunteer and the help of her family at home once her husband, Jesse, calls her to remind her to come home. Chavez was the troop leader of thr girl scouts that started the pantry seven years ago.

While Chavez is away working on the holiday program, volunterr Felicia Nunn cleans up the pantry's outdoor set up Nov. 29, 2022, getting ready for the long process of packing all of the supplies up for the night. Nunn, who only started volunteering at the pantry this summer, is Chavez number 2, stepping up and managing the day to day operations so the pantry can still run.

After the pantry closed at 6 p.m., Nunn manuevers a pallet of sweet potatoes into the church's garage Nov. 29, 2022. As she struggled with the pallet jack, she commented that it needed to be serviced for the third time this year.

Nunn climbs over the pallets of food in the garage, which take up all the space in the garage and don't leave a path to get out once everything is all locked up for the night Nov. 29, 2022. Nunn said she has climbed over larger and more unstable piles before.

IU alumna Abby Malala hugs Jacobs School of Music sophomore Cristina Sarrico after Malala finished reading her speech to the crowd April 2, 2022, in front of the music school’s East Studio Building. “Rarely, ever, are any of us healed in isolation,” Malala said. “Healing is an act of communion. I feel immensely grateful to witness and partake in this act of communal healing on the path toward justice.”

Shatter the Silence representative Shibani Mody speaks to the crowd of demonstrators April 2, 2022, in front of the Jacobs School of Music’s East Studio Building. Mody called for the university to better protect its students from sexual assualt and provide better resources for assisting survivors. “I'm so proud that we have all of us here together,” Mody said. “We're gonna protect each other no matter what.”
